-- Turkish Stocks: Arcelik, Banvit, Nuh Cimento, Yapi Kredi Move
-- B y   B e n j a m i n   H a r v e y
-- 2012-01-04T16:36:26Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-04/turkish-stocks-arcelik-banvit-nuh-cimento-seker-pilic-tav.html
Turkey ’s benchmark  ISE National 100
Index (XU100)  fell 2.5 percent to 51,532.56 at the close in Istanbul,
the steepest decline in three weeks. Of 100 shares in the index,
92 fell, five rose and three were unchanged.  The following were among the active equities on the Turkish
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Arcelik AS (ARCLK)  , Turkey’s largest producer of
household appliances, jumped 4.5 percent to 6.52 liras, the
steepest increase since November. The company was rated “buy”
at UniCredit SpA and UBS AG and favored over another Turkish
electronics producer, Vestel, at Erste Group Bank AG, according
to reports issued today.  Banvit Bandirma Vitaminli Yem Sanayii AS (BANVT)  , a
poultry producer, surged 6.5 percent to 2.96 liras, leading
gains on the ISE100, after  Saudi Arabia  lifted its ban on
Turkish poultry imports, according to a report in Zaman
newspaper.  Seker Pilic & Yem Sanayii Ticaret AS (SKPLC)  , another
poultry company that’s not among Turkey’s top 100 stocks,
rallied 6.7 percent to 1.43 liras, the biggest gain since
October.  Nuh Cimento Sanayi AS (NUHCM)  , Turkey’s largest cement
producer, advanced the most in a month, adding 3.9 percent to
10.70 liras. Parent company Nuh Sirketler Grubu grew 20 percent
in 2011 after its best December ever, and plans to increase its
clinker production capacity by 50 percent, according to an
interview with Chairman Atalay Sahinoglu in Dunya newspaper.  Yapi & Kredi Bankasi AS (YKBNK)  , the lender part-owned
by  UniCredit SpA (UCG) , slipped 5.2 percent to 2.74 liras, leading
declines among banks as Turkey’s banking index retreated 3.3
percent after a 4 percent gain yesterday. UniCredit plunged to
the lowest since March 2009 in Italian trading after setting a
43 percent discount for its rights offer.  To contact the reporter on this story:
